name: 2-ethyl-2-methyl-1,3-propanediol
source: Aldrich Chemical Company; Aldrich Catalog-Handbook of Fine Chemicals; Milwaukee; WI; 1984.
Reason: The compound 2-ethyl-2-methyl-1,3-propanediol consists of a propanediol (a type of alcohol) base structure with additional ethyl and methyl substitutions. The base structure of 1,3-propanediol has a melting point of about -24 degrees Celsius. Each hydroxyl (-OH) group in the alcohol forms strong intramolecular hydrogen bonds, which generally increases the melting point. The two hydroxyl groups would tend to increase this melting point significantly. However, the ethyl and methyl groups are alkyl side chains that provide steric bulk and reduce the tight packing of the molecules, which may reduce the melting point. The methyl group, being smaller, would have a slighter effect than the ethyl group. In particular, an ethyl group on a hydrocarbon typically raises the melting point by a few degrees over a methyl group because of its larger surface area and increased van der Waals interactions. Therefore, we can estimate the incremental effects as follows: Each hydroxyl group may increase the melting point by approximately 50 degrees Celsius, while the ethyl and methyl substitution may decrease the melting point. We will estimate the effect of the ethyl group to decrease the melting point by about 5 degrees Celsius and the methyl group by about 3 degrees Celsius.
Prediction: The predicted melting point for 2-ethyl-2-methyl-1,3-propanediol would be the sum of the base propanediol melting point (-24), the increase due to hydroxyl groups (2 x 50 = 100), and the decreases due to the ethyl (-5) and methyl (-3) groups: -24 + 100 - 5 - 3 = 68 degrees Celsius.
